# Week 1 Progress Report: Project Initiation and Requirement Analysis

## Overview

The first week focused on understanding the PCB prototyping workflow, evaluating existing PCB fabrication methods. Initial efforts were directed toward hands-on PCB fabrication, component identification, and familiarization with the technologies required for the project.

## Activities Performed

1. Manual PCB Fabrication Study

- Fabricated a PCB using the toner transfer (iron heat transfer) method on a copper-clad board.
- Studied the complete workflow involved in conventional DIY PCB manufacturing.
- Analyzed the limitations of manual PCB fabrication techniques.

2. Prototype Circuit Development

- Printed (Ink jet printer) the circuit schematic for a clap-switch application.
- Identified and documented all required electronic components.

3. Technology Research

- Conducted preliminary research on PCB prototyping machines and CNC-based fabrication systems.
- Studied the fundamentals of motion control systems, and PCB engraving processes.
- Explored the role of firmware and controller software used in automated PCB manufacturing systems.

## Key Observations

- The toner transfer method produced inconsistent and extremely thin PCB traces, leading to poor electrical connectivity in several regions.
- Manual PCB fabrication required significant processing time and multiple iterations to achieve acceptable results.
- Trace quality and repeatability were identified as major limitations of the conventional DIY fabrication approach.

## Challenges Encountered

- Difficulty in achieving reliable and uniform PCB trace transfer onto the copper surface.
- Incomplete trace formation resulted in connectivity issues during circuit implementation.
- The overall fabrication process was time-consuming and highly dependent on manual precision.

## Outcomes

- Successfully developed an understanding of the PCB fabrication workflow.
- Completed component identification and circuit prototyping activities.
- Established the technical motivation for developing an automated PCB prototyping machine.

## Next Steps
- Begin the study and implementation of FluidNC firmware for machine control.
- Investigate motion control hardware requirements for the PCB prototyping machine.

